issue.title: Question about averagepool_2d_precomputed_same_upper test

repository.name: onnx
repository.description: Open standard for machine learning interoperability

issue.body: In the test `averagepool_2d_precomputed_same_upper`, the input_shape is [1, 1, 5, 5] and the expected output_shape is [1, 1, 3, 3] when auto_pad = 'SAME_UPPER'. I thought the purpose of using the auto_pad attribute is so that appropriate pads are computed so as to make output_shape the same as the input_shape. Am I missing something ?

body:
Hi @lynic  

It turns out the output shape generated by the runtime is quite valid according to the ONNX spec. For a precedent, please check out the test `averagepool_2d_precomputed_same_upper` in ONNX. It has auto_pad = "SAME_UPPER" and strides > 1 (non-default) and the expected output dimension value contains a value lower than the corresponding input dimension value.

The rationale is like this - 

1) When an autopad value of "SAME_UPPER" or "SAME_LOWER", pads are first computed so that the entire kernel can be accommodated even when operating on a border pixel ("SAME_UPPER"  and "SAME_LOWER" only differ in minor details dictating the distribution of pads to the front and end of the dimension)

2) The output shape is then computed as this: floor(((in_size - kernel + total_padding) / stride)) +1. For the special case of stride == 1, the output shape is the same as the input shape, not otherwise.

References:  https://stackoverflow.com/questions/37674306/what-is-the-difference-between-same-and-valid-padding-in-tf-nn-max-pool-of-t  (I particluary liked the third answer :))

Please re-open this issue if further clarification is required. 

Also, please follow the answers here - https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/1921. I raised this question after seeing the test mentioned above, but I later did some research to find that the test is quite valid, but it might be worthwhile to follow the explanation given by the Deep Learning experts.

cc: @pranavsharma
